Three gradient paths
The path is resolved per subject at runtime in estimation/inner_optimizer.rs::resolve_gradient_method():








Path
Enum variant
When used




AdSingleSnapshot
Enzyme reverse-mode, one per-subject TV snapshot
Subject has no time-varying covariates; analytical PK model


AdEventDriven
Enzyme reverse-mode, per-event TV arrays
Subject has time-varying covariates; model is 1-cpt or 2-cpt IV (bolus/infusion)


Fd
Central finite differences
FERX_NO_AUTODIFF=1, ODE model, model has no tv_fn, or TV-cov on unsupported model



AdSingleSnapshot is the common fast path. AdEventDriven ensures that covariate values at each dose/observation time are correctly propagated through the gradient when a subject’s weight or other covariate changes over time. ODE models currently have no AD path and always use FD.
// Simplified resolve_gradient_method logic
fn resolve_gradient_method(model: &CompiledModel, subject: &Subject) -&gt; InnerGradientMethod {
    #[cfg(not(feature = "autodiff"))]
    return InnerGradientMethod::Fd;

    if model.tv_fn.is_none() { return InnerGradientMethod::Fd; }
    if subject.has_tv_covariates() {
        if supports_event_driven_ad(model.pk_model) {
            InnerGradientMethod::AdEventDriven
        } else {
            InnerGradientMethod::Fd
        }
    } else {
        InnerGradientMethod::AdSingleSnapshot
    }
}
The resolved path is stored in FitResult::gradient_used and exposed to R as fit$gradient_used.

Dual — forward-mode type
ad/dual.rs defines a Dual struct for forward-mode AD through the expression evaluator and PK model equations. It is not the hot Enzyme path — it is used for the model DSL expression interpreter and for contexts where Enzyme is unavailable.
#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy)]
pub struct Dual {
    pub val: f64,
    pub deriv: f64,
}

impl Dual {
    pub fn variable(val: f64) -&gt; Self { Self { val, deriv: 1.0 } }
    pub fn constant(val: f64) -&gt; Self { Self { val, deriv: 0.0 } }
}
Operations implement the chain rule automatically:
let x = Dual::variable(2.0);   // x = 2, dx/dx = 1
let y = x.exp();               // y = e², dy/dx = e²
let z = y * Dual::constant(3.0); // z = 3e², dz/dx = 3e²
Supported operations: exp, ln, sqrt, sin, cos, abs, arithmetic operators, and comparison (treats derivatives as zero for control-flow branching — appropriate for the smooth functions in PK models).

Multi-dose superposition
All analytical models support multiple dose events. The pk/mod.rs dispatcher calls the single-dose solution for each historical dose and sums the contributions at each observation time:
// Conceptual superposition
for dose in &subject.doses {
    let t_since_dose = t_obs - dose.time;
    if t_since_dose &gt;= 0.0 {
        pred += single_dose_solution(dose, t_since_dose, &pk_params);
    }
}

Pipe-based simulation
ex &lt;- ferx_example("warfarin")

sim &lt;- ex$data |&gt;
  ferx_model(ex$model) |&gt;
  ferx_fit(method = "focei") |&gt;
  (\(fit) ferx_simulate(ex$model, ex$data, n_sim = 200, seed = 1, fit = fit))()

Conditional logic
Can I use if / else statements like in NONMEM or nlmixr2?
Yes. Two forms are supported in [individual_parameters] and [odes]:
# Block form
if (WT &gt; 70) {
  CL = TVCL * (WT / 70)^0.75 * exp(ETA_CL)
} else if (SEX == 1) {
  CL = TVCL * 1.2 * exp(ETA_CL)
} else {
  CL = TVCL * exp(ETA_CL)
}

# Inline (ternary) form
CL = if (SEX == 1) TVCL * 1.5 else TVCL
Compared to NONMEM: C-style {braces} and operators (&gt;, ==, &&) rather than Fortran-style IF THEN … ENDIF and .GT., .LE., etc.
Compared to nlmixr2: near-verbatim match — replace &lt;- with =.
Caveat: == and != do bitwise float comparison. They work for integer-coded covariates (SEX == 1) but are unreliable for continuous thresholds. Prefer WT &gt;= 70 && WT &lt; 80 over WT == 75.
Caveat: when a parameter is assigned inside an if block, mu-reference detection is skipped for that parameter. See Individual Parameters.

Event handling
PK dose events create discontinuities in the ODE state that the solver cannot step across. ode/predictions.rs handles this by:

Collecting all dose times and infusion-end times as break points
Integrating segment by segment between consecutive break points
At each bolus dose (EVID = 1), applying the state update: u[cmt] += amt
For infusions, adding +rate to the compartment derivative for the duration of the infusion via a closure wrapper around the user RHS

// Conceptual: infusion added to the RHS during [t_start, t_end]
let rhs_with_infusions = |u, params, t, du| {
    user_rhs(u, params, t, du);
    for (cmt_idx, rate) in &active_infusions {
        du[*cmt_idx] += rate;
    }
};
Break times are constructed so that each integration segment is either fully inside or fully outside every infusion window — no float-equality check is needed at the segment interior.
